    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1918-07-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1918-07-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="856"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d856">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 841.711/2551</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Great Britain</hi> (<persName
                        corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1" type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Laughlin</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">No. 9552</seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1918-07-17">
                            <hi rend="italic">July 17, 1918</hi>
                        </date>. <lb/> [<hi rend="italic">Received August 1.</hi>]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: Referring to my despatch No. 9275, of June 7, and
                    my telegram No. 18 of July 1 replying to the Department’s telegram No. 8508 of
                    June 29, 3 p.m., relative to the censorship of diplomatic correspondence passing
                    in transit through Great Britain, I have the honor to enclose herewith copy of a
                    note from the Foreign Office, dated July 11, 1918,<note n="1" xml:id="d856fn1"
                        >Not printed.</note> in which it is stated, in order to remove any
                    uncertainty which may prevail as to the scope of the Foreign Office circular
                    note of May 31 last,<note n="1" xml:id="d856fn2">Not printed.</note> that it is
                    not intended to apply the measures set forth therein to the correspondence of
                    the United States Government.</p>
                <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="frus1918Supp01v01#p_LIB1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Irwin Laughlin</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
